as somebody who starts
as a person of faith,

00:52:46.680 --> 00:52:51.100
moves away from that but
continues to study, you know,

00:52:51.100 --> 00:52:54.260
these issues as they appear back in time

00:52:54.260 --> 00:52:57.350
and contributes to the
interpretation of text,

00:52:57.350 --> 00:52:58.320
is there an answer there

00:52:58.320 --> 00:53:01.453
that you can help us see a way toward?

00:53:02.440 --> 00:53:05.660
- Yeah, you know, I think
one of the most hopeful signs

00:53:05.660 --> 00:53:10.660
on the religious scene is
that a large number of people

00:53:10.780 --> 00:53:14.650
on the religious right have taken up

00:53:14.650 --> 00:53:16.350
important social issues.

00:53:16.350 --> 00:53:18.980
The reason this is a hopeful sign is

00:53:18.980 --> 00:53:21.720
because the apocalyptic
scenario that I just painted out

00:53:21.720 --> 00:53:24.640
has often led to social complacency.

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:26.450
If, you know, if the end is coming

00:53:26.450 --> 00:53:28.720
and God's gonna make
right all that's wrong,

00:53:28.720 --> 00:53:31.020
and God is gonna resolve
all of our problems,

00:53:31.020 --> 00:53:32.620
then there's no point in us really

00:53:32.620 --> 00:53:34.000
sort of doing much about it now

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:35.700
because we can't do much about it.

00:53:37.019 --> 00:53:40.450
But Christians of the far right
have started realizing that,

00:53:40.450 --> 00:53:44.710
in fact, if God is going
to do this in the future,

00:53:44.710 --> 00:53:46.440
we ought to be doing
something about it now.

00:53:46.440 --> 00:53:47.986
And so you find people

00:53:47.986 --> 00:53:51.343
who are typically conservative Christians,

00:53:52.590 --> 00:53:54.170
who are now supporting things,

00:53:54.170 --> 00:53:57.800
like environmental issues, global warming,

00:53:57.800 --> 00:54:02.800
and concern for world
poverty, and issues like that,

00:54:03.200 --> 00:54:05.670
which have traditionally
been more liberal issues.

00:54:05.670 --> 00:54:07.820
But they're being taken up by
these conservative Christians

00:54:07.820 --> 00:54:10.530
because they realize that
their theology, in fact,

00:54:10.530 --> 00:54:13.030
virtually requires them to be
concerned about these things.

00:54:13.030 --> 00:54:15.940
And so, I see that actually as
one of the more hopeful signs

00:54:15.940 --> 00:54:17.900
on the political scene right now,

00:54:17.900 --> 00:54:21.710
in terms of what's going on
with the religious right.

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:26.430
- How do you advise students
to prepare for the future?

00:54:26.430 --> 00:54:30.200
Because presumably it's not just students

00:54:32.130 --> 00:54:36.990
who wanna become ministers
who are in your classes

00:54:36.990 --> 00:54:39.010
at the University of North Carolina,

00:54:39.010 --> 00:54:40.770
but also people of faith

00:54:40.770 --> 00:54:44.790
who wanna deal, you know, with
the problems of the world.

00:54:44.790 --> 00:54:48.100
Is there some advice
that you would give them,

00:54:48.100 --> 00:54:49.820
in terms of their studies,

00:54:49.820 --> 00:54:53.610
in preparing to address those problems?

00:54:53.610 --> 00:54:57.820
- Yeah, you know, the strange
situation that one is in,

00:54:57.820 --> 00:55:00.900
teaching religion in
a secular institution,

00:55:00.900 --> 00:55:05.850
is that you're teaching a
subject about which, I mean,

00:55:05.850 --> 00:55:08.390
you can't promote a particular
aspect of your subject

00:55:08.390 --> 00:55:11.200
because of the separation
of church and state.

00:55:11.200 --> 00:55:12.110
So, I do get students

00:55:12.110 --> 00:55:14.280
who are planning on going on to ministry,

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:18.745
but by far, my students are
simply people taking the class

00:55:18.745 --> 00:55:20.650
because they're interested
in taking a class

00:55:20.650 --> 00:55:23.680
in the New Testament, you
know, along with their classes

00:55:23.680 --> 00:55:26.490
in philosophy and history
and classics, or whatever.

00:55:26.490 --> 00:55:31.430
But what I try to do in my
classes is actually fairly basic.

00:55:31.430 --> 00:55:34.330
I mean I do try to get
students to understand

00:55:34.330 --> 00:55:36.960
that you have these different
perspectives in the Bible.

00:55:36.960 --> 00:55:39.190
Whether you're a person of faith or not,

00:55:39.190 --> 00:55:41.690
the Bible contains a
lot of different answers

00:55:41.690 --> 00:55:43.060
to a lot of different issues,

00:55:43.060 --> 00:55:45.330
so that I'm trying to get them to see

00:55:45.330 --> 00:55:48.120
that you can't simply, you
know, rest on the Bible,

00:55:48.120 --> 00:55:49.490
the way that many of my students

00:55:49.490 --> 00:55:52.512
in North Carolina think they can do.

00:55:52.512 --> 00:55:54.900
But basically, what I'm trying to do is

00:55:54.900 --> 00:55:57.870
to do what I think every
university professor needs to do,

00:55:57.870 --> 00:56:00.063
which is to get students to think more.

00:56:01.140 --> 00:56:03.670
And teaching Bible in the South is

00:56:03.670 --> 00:56:06.310
a perfect way to get this to happen

00:56:06.310 --> 00:56:09.210
because students come in
with a vested commitment

00:56:09.210 --> 00:56:11.130
and interest in the subject matter,

00:56:11.130 --> 00:56:13.200
unlike almost any other
subject they're taking.

00:56:13.200 --> 00:56:14.740
And if you disabuse them

00:56:14.740 --> 00:56:17.150
of many of their perspectives
and their assumptions,

00:56:17.150 --> 00:56:19.560
it forces them to think.

00:56:19.560 --> 00:56:22.090
So that they have to come
up with solutions themselves

00:56:22.090 --> 00:56:23.410
for things that otherwise they thought

00:56:23.410 --> 00:56:26.230
were gonna be handed to
them on a silver platter.

00:56:26.230 --> 00:56:27.430
This makes them, I think,

00:56:27.430 --> 00:56:31.540
not only more interesting

00:56:31.540 --> 00:56:34.520
and more able to deal
with religious diversity,

00:56:34.520 --> 00:56:37.030
but also with political
diversity, for example.

00:56:37.030 --> 00:56:39.830
Instead of simply accepting
what their parents told them

00:56:40.928 --> 00:56:42.380
about the political situation,

00:56:42.380 --> 00:56:43.610
they're forced to think about it.

00:56:43.610 --> 00:56:45.950
And so, that's really kind of my strategy,

00:56:45.950 --> 00:56:49.420
I think, is to get students
to reflect on big issues

00:56:49.420 --> 00:56:53.060
and to realize that there are
multiple views represented.

00:56:53.060 --> 00:56:55.630
And that one has to come
to some kind of decision

00:56:55.630 --> 00:56:57.461
based on rational thought

00:56:57.461 --> 00:57:01.270
about what position one wants
to take, whether religiously,

00:57:01.270 --> 00:57:03.500
politically, economically,
or anything else.

00:57:03.500 --> 00:57:05.210
- Well, on that note, Bart,

00:57:05.210 --> 00:57:07.010
I wanna thank you very
much for being here.

00:57:07.010 --> 00:57:09.170
Let me show our audience your book again,

00:57:09.170 --> 00:57:10.120
which has actually been

00:57:10.120 --> 00:57:13.230
on the best seller list, God's Problem.

00:57:13.230 --> 00:57:15.400
And I wanna thank you again.

00:57:15.400 --> 00:57:16.490
- Okay, well, thank you.

00:57:16.490 --> 00:57:18.460
- And thank you very much for joining us

00:57:18.460 --> 00:57:20.940
for this Conversation With History.

